# Codebase Summary

## Overview
This portfolio is a single-page Next.js App Router site with a data-driven section model and a calm, minimal visual system. The architecture emphasizes maintainability, responsive behavior, and deployability on Vercel.

## Frameworks and Libraries Used

### Next.js (App Router)
How it is used:
- Provides routing and page assembly through `src/app/layout.tsx` and `src/app/page.tsx`.
- Handles production builds, static generation, and deployment compatibility with Vercel.
- Uses Next metadata API in layout for document title/description.

Why it was chosen:
- First-class Vercel support.
- Strong performance defaults and static prerendering.
- Clean component organization with App Router.

### React + TypeScript
How it is used:
- All UI is split into typed functional components under `src/components`.
- Content contracts are defined in `src/features/portfolio/types.ts`.
- Section content is centralized in `src/features/portfolio/content.ts`.

Why it was chosen:
- Type safety for content schema and component props.
- Easy composability for section-based portfolio architecture.

### Tailwind CSS (plus custom global tokens)
How it is used:
- Utility classes power component styling and responsive layout.
- Design tokens are defined in `src/app/globals.css` (colors, spacing behavior).
- Accent color is fixed to lime (`#A3E635`) per blueprint decisions.

Why it was chosen:
- Fast UI iteration and consistent spacing/layout primitives.
- Easy responsive behavior across desktop/tablet/mobile.

### Framer Motion
How it is used:
- Included as part of the planned motion system and design direction.
- Current scrollytelling interaction is implemented with lightweight browser APIs and CSS transitions.

Why it was chosen:
- Provides room for richer controlled motion if deeper animation polish is added later.

### Lucide React
How it is used:
- Installed for icon support in UI/navigation patterns.

Why it was chosen:
- Lightweight and consistent icon system.

## Key Architectural Decisions

### 1) Data-driven content model
Decision:
- Keep portfolio copy and link targets in one source file: `src/features/portfolio/content.ts`.

Benefit:
- Non-structural updates (links, text, project placeholders) are fast and low risk.

### 2) Section-oriented component architecture
Decision:
- Build each homepage region as its own section component (`HeroSection`, `ExpertiseSection`, `ProofBlockSection`, `PhilosophySection`, `ContactSection`).

Benefit:
- Predictable structure, easier testing, and easy future section replacement.

### 3) Reusable proof-block primitives
Decision:
- Separate proof-block internals into dedicated components (`FeatureList`, `StackTagList`, `ProofMediaFrame`, `ProofCTAGroup`).

Benefit:
- Consistent project presentation and easier migration from placeholders to real projects.

### 4) Scrollytelling interaction model
Decision:
- Add a client-side `ScrollytellingController` that supports:
  - normal scrolling
  - keyboard cycling (`Space`) on desktop
  - touch tap-to-advance on mobile

Benefit:
- Narrative flow between sections without removing default browser navigation behavior.

### 5) Accessibility and interaction safeguards
Decision:
- Keep skip link navigation, focus ring styling, and avoid hijacking interactive controls during scrollytelling.
- Email action in Contact copies to clipboard and shows confirmation feedback.

Benefit:
- Better keyboard usability and clear user feedback.

### 6) Vercel deployment alignment
Decision:
- Keep default Next.js deployment path with static prerendering.
- Keep image remote pattern configured for Unsplash assets in `next.config.ts`.

Benefit:
- Straightforward GitHub to Vercel CI/CD with minimal custom config.

